04607nam a2200661Ia 9781501724169DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017241697 a10.7591/97815017241692doi  a(DE-B1597)515050  a(OCoLC)1083616349  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR275.C42bF69 2003eb 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a820.9/27/09022231 aFowler, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiterary Character :bThe Human Figure in Early English Writing /cElizabeth Fowler. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 halftone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Textual Debts -- tIntroduction: The Arguments of Person -- t1. Character and the Habituation of the Reader: The Pardoner's Thought Experiment -- t2. Persons in the Creation of Social Bonds: Agency and Civil Death in Piers Plowman -- t3. The Temporality of Social Persons: Value in "The Tunnyng of Elynour Rummynge" -- t4. Architectonic Person and the Grounds of the Polity in The Faerie Queene -- tAfterword: The Obligations of Persons -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChaucer introduces the characters of the Knight and the Prioress in the General Prologue to The Canterbury Tales. Beginning with these familiar figures, Elizabeth Fowler develops a new method of analyzing literary character. She argues that words generate human figures in our reading minds by reference to paradigmatic cultural models of the person. These models—such as the pilgrim, the conqueror, the maid, the narrator—originate in a variety of cultural spheres. A concept Fowler terms the "social person" is the key to understanding both the literary details of specific characterizations and their indebtedness to history and culture.Drawing on central texts of medieval and early modern England, Fowler demonstrates that literary characters are created by assembling social persons from throughout culture. Her perspective allows her to offer strikingly original readings of works by Chaucer, Langland, Skelton, and Spenser, and to reformulate and resolve several classic interpretive problems. In so doing, she reframes accepted notions of the process and the consequences of reading.Developing insights from law, theology, economic thought, and political philosophy, Fowler's book replaces the traditional view of characters as autonomous individuals with an interpretive approach in which each character is seen as a battle of many archetypes. According to Fowler, the social person provides the template that enables authors to portray, and readers to recognize, the highly complex human figures that literature requires.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172416940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724169/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles